Hello everyone

I am in trouble to remove a hyperlink underline in a page using a fontawesome icon.

I tried use the css configuration like

*HTML
	<li> <a href="http://www.apple.com"> <span class="icon fa-play-circle-o major style3"><span class="style3">Dolor</span></span></li>
*CSS
	a:link, a:visited { 
			text-decoration: none;
			cursor: auto;
	}

I am attaching an image that shows the problem on my site. When I hover the mouse the underline link disappears but not when the mouse is not hovering.

![iconsfa](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/539561/7107162/cb1fdfe6-e131-11e4-8003-95c4453495c1.png)

### Description

Currently the [UWSGIMetricsCollector](https://github.com/zalando/connexion/blob/53908d30e566ccb81d73d3e27b461f407a8a8d31/connexion/decorators/metrics.py#L33) reporting will create a metrics key with status_code=500 for all exception thrown in the underlying call (BadRequest, Unauthorized, etc.)

### Expected behaviour
If an HTTPException is thrown in the underlying function, use the status code of the exception to report in the metrics. If an unknown exception is thrown map it to a specific "unkown exception" metrics key.

E.g.:
```json
"timers": {
    "connexion.response.401.GET.state.{id}": {
        "count": 2
    },
    "connexion.response.unknown-exception.GET.state.{id}": {
        "count": 2
    }
}
```


### Actual behaviour
**Any** exception is mapped to status code 500 as that is the default:
```json
"timers": {
    "connexion.response.500.GET.state.{id}": {
        "count": 2
    }
}
```

### Solution suggestion
Maybe something like this would help?
```python
@functools.wraps(function)
def wrapper(request):
    status = 'unknown-exception'
    start_time_s = time.time()
    try:
        response = function(request)
        status = response.status_code
    except HTTPException as http_e:
        status = str(http_e.code)
        raise http_e
    finally:
        end_time_s = time.time()
        delta_s = end_time_s - start_time_s
        delta_ms = delta_s * 1000
        key = '{status}.{suffix}'.format(status=status, suffix=self.key_suffix)
        uwsgi_metrics.timer(self.prefix, key, delta_ms)
    return response

Because `TaskIdentityFingerprintStrategy` uses `self.subsystem_dependencies_iter` to collect subsystem scopes to get options for, it doesn't recurse into the closure of subsystem dependencies.

@benjyw suggested that moving option fingerprinting onto `Optionable` would address both cases, and give both tasks and subsystems a fingerprint for free.

Related to #2531; if fingerprinting moved onto `Optionable`, subsystems would also gain the "implementation version" fingerprinting.

