First of all, I've been following ExaBGP for a while now and recently started replacing our 'trigger' routers with ExaBGP for RTBH and internal null routes.  It's worked well so far, but I'm having problems getting the routes from Exa to compare with what is currently in the master DB: there are multiple servers running in each ASN that are kept up-to-date via message queues when people add/remove/modify the routes via an HTTP form.  I periodically want to compare the master DB with what Exa has and make sure the correct IP addresses are being being blocked.

The way the routes are initially being added to the config is I start the daemon up and 'bulk' add via an 'announce attribute' and have all the nulls in the NLRI.  At that point, when something is received, via the message queue, I post to the HTTP API I have running, which also works great.

The problem comes when I want to grab the routes and compare them to the DB.  I have a 'dirty' script to grab the routes:

```
def get_routes(peer):
    post('http://127.0.0.1:{0}'.format(peer.port), {'command': 'show routes'})
    time.sleep(10)
    lines = []
    routes = []
    for line in reversed(open(os.path.join(settings.BASE_DIR, "exabgp_{0}.log".format(peer.port))).readlines()):
        if 'show routes' in line:
            break
        else: lines.append(line)
    for line in lines:
        if 'Responding to http_api' in line:
            routes.append(line.split()[9])
    return routes
```
I couldn't figure out a more elegant way of grabbing the returned routes from the sys.stdout in the post, so I'm grabbing them from the logs the best I can. (any suggestions here would be great!)

